{"doc":{"isMarkdown":true,"isTranslated":false,"isActive":true,"flaws":{},"title":"Canvas","mdn_url":"/en-US/docs/Glossary/Canvas","locale":"en-US","native":"English (US)","sidebarHTML":"","body":[{"type":"prose","value":{"id":null,"title":null,"isH3":false,"content":"<p>The <strong>canvas element</strong> is part of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML5\" class=\"external\" rel=\" noopener\">HTML5</a> and allows for dynamic, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scripting_language\" class=\"external\" rel=\" noopener\">scriptable</a> <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rendering_(computer_graphics)\" class=\"external\" rel=\" noopener\">rendering</a> of 2D and 3D shapes and <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bitmap\" class=\"external\" rel=\" noopener\">bitmap</a> images.</p>\n<p>It is a low level, procedural model that updates a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bitmap\" class=\"external\" rel=\" noopener\">bitmap</a> and does not have a built-in <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scene_graph\" class=\"external\" rel=\" noopener\">scene graph</a>. It provides an empty graphic zone on which specific <a href=\"/en-US/docs/Glossary/JavaScript\">JavaScript</a> <a href=\"/en-US/docs/Glossary/API\">APIs</a> can draw (such as Canvas 2D or <a href=\"/en-US/docs/Glossary/WebGL\">WebGL</a>).</p>"}},{"type":"prose","value":{"id":"see_also","title":"See also","isH3":false,"content":"<ul>\n  <li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canvas_element\" class=\"external\" rel=\" noopener\">Canvas</a> on Wikipedia</li>\n  <li><a href=\"/en-US/docs/Web/API/Canvas_API/Tutorial\">The Canvas tutorial on MDN</a></li>\n  <li>The HTML <a href=\"/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/canvas\"><code>&lt;canvas&gt;</code></a> element on MDN</li>\n  <li><a href=\"/en-US/docs/Web/API/Canvas_API\">The Canvas general documentation on MDN</a></li>\n  <li><a href=\"/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D\"><code>CanvasRenderingContext2D</code></a>: The canvas 2D drawing 